segments.text: I think we were talking about senior boots and how much they cost.
I think seventy-five dollars.
And of course then you had to buy the breeches to go with them.
Oh, that wasn't standard issue?
No, you had to pay for that.
That wasn't government issue.
So you not only had to buy the boots, but you had to buy the breeches.
And the summer breeches and the winter ones.
So there was that expense.
So it was not an inconsequential thing.
How did you and your senior buddies, what special care did y'all give to those people?
We took care of them.
They always had a special place in the room.
The big decision was, when your senior year was over, what were you going to do with it?
Everybody wanted to keep it, but we all needed the money.
And I sold mine, and I don't remember who.
Do you remember how much you got for them?
No.
During your senior year, about how often did you wear those boots?
Gosh, well, every parade function.
Every football game?
Every football, oh yeah, every football game.
And if you were out of town or on a date or something like that, you'd want to be sure to wear them.
every opportunity you could without being just gauche about it.
And you hadn't yet met this special girl from Waco?
No.
Well, yeah, I had.
Virginia and I met that one quarter I went to Beto when my folks were living up in the ranch, but it never materialized until later.
Let's see, do you remember going to Muster on campus?
I don't have a specific recollection of it.
And that may be because of a muster I made.
I don't know whether I'd come home.
I don't have a specific recollection of the muster.
I do have my 53 Union muster.
Oh, that was fantastic.
Right, you're senior ring.
Oh, big deal.
How much did it cost?
I want to say it.
It was less than a hundred.
How did you feel when you put that on?
Oh man, big deal.
Why are Aggie rings special?
I think one of the reasons is that you can get it only if you go to school and satisfy certain requirements.
You can't go to the jewelry store and buy it.
You can't go to the bookstore and buy it.
It just has that tradition.
Have you ever lost yours?
No, never have.
Any good ring stories about where somebody saw it?
No, but it saved my finger one time.
I was in the tank, and the hatch fell, and it hit the ring, and if it hadn't been for the ring, I lost my finger.
I remember that, because I bent it a little bit, and I had to get it straightened out.
Then your senior year final review.
Very emotional.
Describe how, why.
Well, of course, you know it's the end of it.
And of course, at that time, the war had already started in Korea.
And I knew, you know, step off campus.
This is May of 1950.
No, I didn't graduate until August.
August of 50?
Yeah, August of 50.
Oh, so the war just started then?
The war just started in June.
So it had, I had taken a regular, it was offered and took a regular commission.
But, you know, there was, that sort of put a, several of us had gone off to, you know, interview for jobs and things like that.
I know I went to Dallas and interviewed with P&G.
And then the war started.
your future all of a sudden was totally changed.
There wasn't any choice about where you were going to go or what you were going to do.
So it had that kind of feeling about doing it because you knew you were going to have to do it immediately.
But it was an emotional time.
Did parents come, did family come for final review and commencement?
See, graduating in August, there was final review, but my parents didn't come up.
I think maybe, I started to say that, I think maybe my parents came up one time for Mother's Day.
And I'm pretty sure my mother was there.
So, did you ever go across the stage for commencement?
To get my diploma?
Not to get a diploma.
I don't think they had it.
I did go to get commissioned.
I got a picture of that.
Now that was done in the spring?
No, that was done probably in August.
Oh really?
Yeah.
Alright, as you and your buddies were, during your senior year, as you all began to talk about the future, how well prepared did you think A&M had made you for the future?
What did you think?
I felt good about it.
because I had that offer from P&G, which was a good offer.
I didn't know what I wanted to do really, but John Taylor and I were good friends all through school.
We both went to P&G and both of us were made offers.
What was the foundation for your optimism about the A&M education, the A&M preparation?
I think I would say
that it was an awareness that a graduate of A&M was well regarded.
I think A&M had a good reputation in the, quote, marketplace.
We felt more so than other schools.
And I don't know whether that was really true, but that was kind of the feeling we had, fed to us really by former students.
He always felt you were going to get a fair break.
As you look back now, what preparation did A&M give to you for the real world?
What was special about A&M?
What evidence did you find?
I don't know that this is a fair view of it, but I think you've got an appreciation of how people can work together.
It was less of a frat-type school, if that's one way to put it.
We were pretty serious.
I mean, we had a lot of good times, and that's all right, but I think the whole campus
was serious about its education.
Maybe that was flavored by the fact that there was some other veterans.
But I think we always felt we got a good education.
Obviously, some schools were better than others.
I think the business school was marginal at best.
Looking back on it, I don't know what it was.
But there was still enough goodness, if that's the word, about
the other disciplines and the guys you were with.
You knew, for engineers, you know, I roomed with an engineer, you knew what the difficulties were and the disciplines that they went through.
You felt that anybody who came through and got a degree there had earned something and that it was well regarded on the outside.
Did A&M help you get that
P&G offer?
Did A&M help people get jobs there?
They did have a placement service, certainly nothing like it is now.
And I'm trying to think who was in charge of it.
I don't want to say Wendell Horsley, but that may have been when I was on the staff.
I don't know whether Wendell was there when I was in school or not.
Again, that was all King's accident at the war study for those of us who were in the Corps.
What creates Aggie spirit, Aggie loyalty?
That's a good question.
I think it's a respect for the institution, a respect for people who have
immerse themselves in the institution in whatever form they choose.
I think it is the recognition of the continuity of fellowship for camaraderie.
And there's a singleness of association.
There was.
I don't know now whether that's still the case or not.
But at that time, it was really, we kind of flew together because there wasn't anything else to do there.
We were perforce united at a location pursuing, in a sense, our own individual goals.
pursuing it in concert with a lot of other people.
And I don't know as the school has grown if that's still the case or not.
While the go home machine was turned off, we were talking about the inclusiveness of the student body.
Describe the diversity of the student body when you were there.
Obviously it wasn't diverse.
as diverse then as it is now.
There were no blacks on campus.
There were not that many Mexican Americans, but I think that was probably, we probably had as many as any large state institution because you could go there and not have to spend a lot of money.
It was not an expensive school to go to.
the Mexican-Americans who were there were totally absorbed into the culture of the place.
There was no, absolutely no discrimination.
What about other groups, Jews, Catholics, Protestants?
I don't recall any instance of any type of difficulty in none whatsoever.
Basically, in terms of their economic background, can you generalize about Aggie?
Most of us were from middle economic ranges or lower.
There were a few.
One guy had an airplane.
Oh boy.
He was the Colonel of the Corps in 51.
A.D. Martin had an airplane.
What kind?
Cessna 172.
He had a car.
He never let it go to his head.
Because one time he threw us all down the rail.
We had a big party down the rail.
But when I was on WTAW, the best guy on the station was the owner, Dick Gottlieb.
He went on and had quite a career in radio.
A Jewish.
One of the guys on the battalion staff, his name was Gollum, went on to become, I think, a big editor with
a person's religion or economic background.
There just wasn't any.
I don't know what the term would be.
Were they urban or rural?
I think largely rural.
Small town.
I think you're right for that.
In terms of if we had to
We're not talking about politics now.
We're talking about change, receptivity, or...
If you're not talking about politics, I would say that there was a feeling that there was a job to be done.
You had to get through school.
You were fortunate to be where you were.
You didn't, you were not looking for windmills to tilt.
That wasn't important.
The important thing was to get all the way through school.
All right, now, in politics, let's generalize.
What were they like?
Well, I suspect if they had any preference, they were mostly Democrats then.
I'm going to take a small break.
Let's go back to your senior year.
Your roommate was the Corps Commander.
What kind of routine did a Corps Commander have in those years?
What did the Corps Commander have to worry about?
About everything.
His name was Doyle Aband from Laredo.
Very modest background.
He was a quantum engineering major.
He was smart, mature beyond his years.
He was not a veteran, but he was a very mature young man.
He reported, of course, to Colonel Boatner.
Boatner used him.
He just delegated things to him and held him responsible for what went on in the Corps.
Despite his very modest background, he had no difficulty whatsoever in talking to big people, former students, dignitaries would come to campus because he got called in and all that sort of thing.
Handled himself beautifully.
He was an unusual young man.
Were there major crises that he had to deal with, which you would call them?
Not that I remember.

He was so highly respected within the Corps that if anything, and I can't think of anything specific, but if there were anything that threatened to cause a problem, he was sufficient unto himself to take care of it.
Were there any pranks tried on the Corps commander or his roommate?
Since I was his roommate, not on him.
I used to get drowned on occasion just because of the battalion stuff, but I knew that.
I could tell it was coming.
In terms of making noise or anything else, was the area where y'all were in the dorm, was that kind of fish didn't bother that area very much?
No, no, no, they didn't.
I don't ever remember them coming.
Describe...
the routine for meals for the Corps staff in Duncan Binding Hall?
I think we ate together.
I think we ate together as a group.
It's hard for me to separate.
I'm thinking more of the time that I wasn't on the Corps staff, but we ate together as a group.
But it would, I would say it would be very civil.
I mean, we
Did y'all get adequate helpings?
We didn't get any special treatment.
No, you didn't get any?
No, no.
Really?
No, no.
No, we didn't get any favoritism in that respect.
And you don't remember his ever being called out in the middle of the night to work on something?
No.
He was uniquely qualified for the job.
I don't know where he got his maturity.
But he really, he had it and he was so highly respected within the Corps by the regimental commanders and by the military staff.
And there was a, were you all aware your junior year of a comparatively serious routine of reviewing to make the Corps commander selection?
Yes, I don't remember what it was, but he was
I think they had been earmarked early in his junior year.
Those kind of guys kind of stood out early on.
Did y'all have a fish to come and take care of your room when you were seniors?
No.
No, we didn't do that.
See, again, Boatner was so determined to stamp out any kind of hazing.
He never was totally successful, but he did.
And for that reason, no, we didn't have any of that in the course of that.
Were you all careful to see to it that your room never had any violations or regulations?
I don't think we made an effort.
We just never did.
Yeah.
So it was, you know, we had a response.
And again, I think the fact that during those years,
There were so many veterans there who were so serious about their education.
We, being the veterans, kind of lifted the maturity of the whole group.
We said, without consciously making that, but we set an example that other guys kind of rose to.
And so... Was smoking in the dormitories allowed then?
Yes.
I don't remember much of it, but it was allowed, sure.
Okay, back, I don't have many questions left.
Can you think of any important topics we have not yet included?
No, no... You ask a lot of questions.
You didn't make any whiz-bang trips to New York or California or the other side of the world or anything like that?
No, we didn't do any of that, you know.
During the summers, what did you do?
Well, of course, one summer...
Being in the Corps, we had to go to Fort Hood.
At Fort Hood, how did you Aggies compare with the other ROTC students?
We thought we were better than the rest of them by far.
I'll throw this in.
At A&M, at the time I was there, we had a couple of tanks to work with.
I learned to drive a tank at A&M.
Of course, further at Fort Hood.
That saved my life.

in Korea, because we lost so many people when the Chinese came in, and we were trying to withdraw, and we didn't have, we lost a lot of people, and I ended up driving, I was a lieutenant, but I ended up driving a tank, because we were 24 hours on the road, in the dark, mountain roads, and I knew how to drive a tank.
Another point, when I went to Korea, I went over with six other guys, a total of six of us, all from other ROTC schools,
None of them had any idea what they were up against.
I sat down the night before we went into our battalion, and I showed them how to get into a tank and what they would find there, and how to shoot a machine gun.
They'd never had any, they were quartermasters and finance people.
The A&M saved my life in that sense.
Do you remember when you first heard about the war beginning in Korea?
Oh, yeah, the day it happened, you know.
That was such a traumatic thing.
We knew right away that forget about P&G.
Were you here that summer?
You were at A&M that summer?
I was at A&M, yeah, because I had to go through to August to finish.
And you heard about it on the radio?
Would have to have been the radio, yeah.
Since the Corps wasn't there that summer, did Boatner or anybody else call you?
No, we weren't notified in any respect.
You just knew intuitively what was ahead.
It wasn't like, do you remember where you were when Pearl Harbor happened?
It kind of came on, it took a couple of days to realize, hey, we're going to get into this thing.
And from there on out, everything changed.
All right, let's see.
If you were a consultant to the A&M leadership today, what advice would you give them about
continuing A&M, how to continue A&M's progress.
What do you think A&M ought to do or not do, continue to do or start doing in the future?
Oh gosh, that's difficult because, you know, I don't really know what all they're doing now, but I would say that a real
concerted effort needs to be made to keep the core at A&M.
And I say that just because I think it is so much a part of the history of the school.
It gives the school a uniqueness that few institutions have.
You've got the Citadel, and you've got West Point, Annapolis, and so on.
And they have to move with the times.
But given the patriotic speech here, we need in the armed services today people who come from a, quote, a civilian kind of background.
I think you need that leaven in the military forces.
And so I think A&M has a responsibility to provide that as it has in the past.
That doesn't mean there isn't a marvelous opportunity for people who don't want to be in the Corps.
But I think that needs to get special attention because it is a uniqueness.
What else?
From what I see, I think what is being done now seems to be the right sort of thing.
I mean, institutions have to change.
And I think A&M is changing appropriately, and of course my source is just basically the Alumni Magazine, which I think is a fine publication.
It's going to be difficult to keep the standards up, I guess, except
that just the physical number of limitations of students coming in is going to be a filter and we'll continue to have good people.
I think there seems to be an effort to try and keep a vision ahead, try to adapt it to a terribly changing society.
I think our isolation in Brazos County is probably a good thing in that respect, because you don't go there unless you want to go.
If someone walked up to you and gave you a check for a million dollars with one restriction, you had to pass it to Texas A&M, but you could decide what to be done with it.
Or if you could make a
Really, big gift to A&M.
What would you want that gift to do?
What would be your highest priority projects?
I think that I would put it into scholarships for students who went into the Corps.
I think the other parts are going to take care of themselves.
They're taking care of themselves.
But I think that's so important that anything that will attract good people and with a commitment to the Corps of Cadets is probably as much as can be done for A&M with one single check.
How would you select the recipients of those?
I think it would have to be a combination of need, academics, and a commitment to the core.
To what former students, faculty, advisors, etc., do you feel greatest debt of gratitude and why?
Earl Rudder.
Why?
He is the man, as much as any one person, responsible for taking A&M out of a good but not spectacular institution and giving it the foundation for being a great institution.
Who else?
Perhaps to you personally.
Are there others that meant something special to you personally?
Now, of all the people that I associate with at A&M, Earl Rudder stands head and shoulders above the rest of them.
All right, then my last question is, what feelings do you hold in your heart today for Texas A&M?
I think I'd have to say that I was very, very fortunate that I ended up there.
I could end up a lot of different places.
And I don't think that any place that I know of could have given me more for what lay ahead of me than A&M did.
And I still have many, many good friends.
So I think that's it.
